// apps/render_assistant/shaders/wap_warp.comp
// STAGE-41 (warp-at-presenter): app-local port of the pillar's optical_flow_warp.comp,
// run ON THE PRESENTER (G) per output-clock tick at the tick's EXACT fractional phase t.
//
// The pillar builds the MV + SAD field on B (the block-match); in WAP mode F ships ONLY
// that field (MV+SAD, ~0.5MB/set) to G instead of 7 pre-warped interps (~58MB/set over the
// x4). G holds the two pair reals + the MV/SAD as sampled images and re-warps at the exact
// per-tick phase. This subsumes the pre-generated 1/N grid and its uniq-coverage defect:
// every tick synthesises the phase due at THAT refresh, no rounding.
//
// Logic is the pillar warp's, verbatim in spirit — BOTH gates and the SAME unconditional
// barrier pattern (the divergence trap is documented below; do NOT early-return before the
// barrier). The only differences are app-side bindings (4 separate sampler2D inputs + an
// rgba8 storage output) and the push-constant block carrying {res_ceil, conf_improv,
// agreement, t, soft_gate} so the presenter sets t per tick.
//
// ── STAGE-46: soft-gate mode (push-selected, soft_gate>0.5) ──────────────────
//   The binary per-8×8-block keep/freeze decision pulses motion at the source rate
//   (lag-8 autocorr). A continuous blend wins judder↔hallucination both:
//     · each gate's margin maps through a smoothstep centred on its push threshold
//       (improvement_frac, agreement_threshold) → w_conf, w_agree.
//     · isolated-block suppression: a pixel whose own source-disagreement d_pixel far
//       exceeds the TILE mean d_tile (it disagrees with all its tile neighbours) fades
//       toward freeze (w_neigh) — kills stray wrong-MV stamps at disocclusion contours.
//       Uses ONLY the existing s_d/d_tile statistic — no new shared array.
//     · w = w_conf · w_agree · w_neigh; out = mix(blend, warp, w).
//   soft_gate ≤ 0.5 (default OFF) takes the EXACT original binary branch below
//   (byte-identical to the pre-STAGE-46 hard path — no arithmetic change).
//
// ── STAGE-48: bidirectional flow + occlusion classification (push-selected, occl_thresh>0.0) ─
//   Until now A's warp approximated BACKWARD flow by negating the forward field — the SAME
//   field served both directions, so disocclusion rims ghosted and d_ab/commit was a blind
//   proxy. STAGE-48 ships a TRUE backward MV field (binding 5, built on B as a second
//   record_optical_flow with swapped views) and classifies every output pixel by fwd↔bwd
//   consistency BEFORE the 47b/c commit safety net runs:
//     · Follow the forward flow: at this grid uv, mvf = MV_fwd(uv) (full-res pixel units, the
//       same the warp samples). The content at uv in prev (A) lands at uv_in_cur = uv + mvf/sz
//       in cur (B). Sample the backward field there: mvb = MV_bwd(uv_in_cur). A consistent
//       (co-visible) pixel round-trips: mvf + mvb ≈ 0. Error e = length(mvf + mvb) in PIXEL
//       units (the stored MV unit). Consistent iff e ≤ occl_thresh (default 1.5 px ≈ block-scale).
//     · consistent → leave warp_result/blend_result untouched: the existing average + the 47c
//       machinery downstream run UNCHANGED (co-visible content wants the sharp average).
//     · inconsistent → decide OWNERSHIP via symmetric round-trips:
//         e_fwd = the forward round-trip residual computed above (prev→cur→prev).
//         e_bwd = the backward round-trip residual (cur→prev→cur): at uv take mvb0 = MV_bwd(uv),
//                 land at uv_in_prev = uv + mvb0/sz, read mvf2 = MV_fwd(uv_in_prev),
//                 e_bwd = length(mvb0 + mvf2).
//       fwd round-trips but bwd does not (e_fwd ≤ occl_thresh < e_bwd) → the content is owned
//       by PREV (it exists in A, is occluded/absent in B) → the PREV side (A_samp / texture(prev,uv))
//       is the WINNER. bwd round-trips but fwd does not → owned by CUR → B_samp / texture(cur, uv)
//       is the winner.
//       ── STAGE-49 CHANGE (was a HARD pick): the winner is no longer assigned outright. The hard
//         pick snapped at the e==occl_thresh boundary → a seam along disocclusion rims. Per FSR3's
//         shipping practice (dossier F6: two disocclusion masks, mask-WEIGHTED blending), the
//         application is now CONTINUOUS in the round-trip-error ratio r = e_loser/(e_winner+0.25):
//         w_side = smoothstep(1.0, 3.0, r); warp_result = mix(average, winner_sample, w_side),
//         blend_result = mix(cross_fade, winner_real, w_side). r≥3 (loser ≫ winner) = fully
//         one-sided (the old hard behavior); r≈1 (near-tie at the rim's soft edge) blends both
//         sides back toward the average. The classification is UNCHANGED — only the application is
//         softened (the operator A/Bs hard-vs-weighted via build version; the off-path is untouched).
//       NEITHER round-trips → leave both as-is → fall through to the 47b/c commit machinery
//       (the safety net handles the truly-ambiguous case unchanged).
//   occl_thresh == 0.0 (default OFF, = --bidir not set) takes NONE of this — the whole block is
//   gated on occl_thresh > 0.0 (a uniform push value), byte-identical to pre-STAGE-48. The bwd
//   sampler (binding 5) is still bound (a valid image), but unread when off.
//
// ── STAGE-50: divergence-directed disocclusion pick (push-selected, div_eps>0.0) ──────────
//   The residual after STAGE-48 is a thin CONSTANT trail of speckle behind moving objects: the
//   "NEITHER round-trips" class (genuine disocclusion slivers) falls to the 47b/c commit fallback
//   = nearest real IN TIME, which for a disocclusion is the wrong side half the ticks. The physics
//   picks the side deterministically: the forward-MV field DIVERGES (positive divergence) where
//   content is being revealed (expansion — the background is ALWAYS present in cur/B) and CONVERGES
//   (negative divergence) where it is being occluded (the background is ALWAYS present in prev/A).
//   Still 100% real content — only the SELECTION criterion changes in the ni-ni sliver; no invented
//   fill (no stretch/inpaint) enters here.
//     · Compute div = ∂(mv.x)/∂x + ∂(mv.y)/∂y of the forward field by central differences over
//       ±1 MV-GRID texel (the step in uv = 1/textureSize(u_motion_vectors,0) — queried, never
//       hardcoded). Units: pixels (the stored MV unit) per MV-grid texel.
//         div >  +div_eps → revealed  → warp_result = B_samp, blend_result = texture(cur,  uv).
//         div <  −div_eps → occluded  → warp_result = A_samp, blend_result = texture(prev, uv).
//         |div| ≤ div_eps (ambiguous) → leave both as-is → fall through to 47b/c unchanged.
//   Lives INSIDE the STAGE-48 "neither round-trips" case and is additionally gated on div_eps > 0.0
//   (a uniform push value): div_eps == 0.0 (default OFF, = --fill-div not set) reads NONE of this and
//   computes NO extra taps — byte-identical to STAGE-48. Requires --bidir (no neither-class without
//   the fwd↔bwd classification); the app errors out on --fill-div without --bidir. The added cost is
//   4 extra MV texture taps, ONLY inside the already-rare neither-class branch.
//
// ── STAGE-49: candidate-rescue (push-selected, rescue_on>0.5; armed only with commit) ─────────
//   The 47b/c commit drops a sub-block feature to source cadence (or a displaced fetch) whenever the
//   8×8 block MV is wrong for it — but that feature's TRUE vector usually lives in an ADJACENT block
//   (the duck's body MV dominated its tile; the duck's eye carries the eye's MV one cell over). So
//   BEFORE the commit fallback fires, a failing pixel tries the 8 NEIGHBOR block MVs as candidates —
//   per-pixel MV by SELECTION, the production sub-block pattern (dossier F1 = Qualcomm US8537283's
//   neighbor-block-MV selection; F0 = 3DRS/Philips block erosion):
//     · The pixel "fails" iff d_ab is in/above the 47c band (d_ab > 0.75·commit_thresh) AND rescue is
//       on (rescue_on>0.5, which the app sets only with commit armed). The whole loop is gated inside
//       the existing `commit_thresh>0` block, so the default path is byte-identical.
//     · For each of the 8 neighbors (3×3 fwd-grid cells, center excluded — its MV already failed),
//       sample mv_c = MV_fwd(uv + offset·mv_texel) where mv_texel = 1/textureSize(u_motion_vectors,0),
//       re-warp A_c = prev[uv − t·mv_c/sz] and B_c = cur[uv + (1−t)·mv_c/sz] (the SAME sign/scale as
//       the primary warp), score d_c = max-channel |A_c − B_c|, track the best (lowest d_c).
//     · best d_c ≤ commit_thresh → RESCUED: warp_result = (1−t)·A_c_best + t·B_c_best (the candidate's
//       average — the feature found its vector) and the commit mix is SKIPPED for this pixel (wc→0).
//       No candidate passes → proceed to 47b/c exactly as before.
//   blend_result is left untouched by rescue (it stays the soft-gate fallback path). Cost: confined to
//   the already-failing branch, 8 candidates × (1 MV tap + 2 color taps) worst case. rescue_on ≤ 0.5
//   (default OFF) reads NONE of this — byte-identical to STAGE-50.
//
// ── STAGE-52: the frame-holon — global affine motion model (push-selected, gme_on > 0.5) ──────
//   A cheap GLOBAL parametric model fitted per pair on the CPU (F thread) from the whole fwd MV grid
//   by IRLS least squares (object outliers reweighted): mv_model(gx,gy) = (a + b·gx + c·gy,
//   d + e·gx + f·gy), gx,gy the mv-grid coords. The 6 params ride the push ({gme_a..gme_f}); the
//   shader evaluates the model at this pixel's grid position (gme_model_mv → gx = uv·G − 0.5, the
//   bilinear texel coord, matching the CPU fit's lattice). Two consumers, BOTH gated on gme_on>0.5:
//     · RESCUE CANDIDATE (inside the STAGE-49 rescue loop): the model MV is ONE extra candidate,
//       scored by the SAME windowed SAD and competing for best_s like a neighbour. A fast camera pan
//       moves more than the block-match search window → the local MV and all 8 neighbours are wrong;
//       the global model (robust to the moving objects) recovers the camera/background MV. Armed only
//       with --rescue (it lives in the rescue loop); without it gme still fits + masks + fill-div-assists.
//     · FILL-DIV BACKGROUND MV (inside the STAGE-50 neither-class disocclusion branch): the revealed
//       background's true motion is the camera/background motion (the model), NOT the local MV (the
//       occluding object's). The owning real is sampled at the MODEL displacement instead of raw uv —
//       the documented MEMC background-extension (dossier F5). Gated on gme_on so fill-div alone
//       (gme off) is byte-identical (the model offset collapses to zero, raw-uv samples kept).
//   gme_on == 0.0 (default OFF, = --gme not set) reads NONE of this — byte-identical to STAGE-49.
//   The per-block dissidence mask (|mv − model|) is built + shipped to wapDISA on the HOST side; the
//   warp does NOT sample it yet (STAGE-53's boundary-first compositing will).
//
// ── STAGE-47: commit-don't-hedge mode (push-selected, commit_thresh>0.0) ─────
//   Root cause of the ghost eye (operator, 2026-06-12): our TWO averaging layers.
//     (1) warp_result = (1−t)·A_samp + t·B_samp shows BOTH samples whenever the 8×8
//         block MV is wrong for a sub-block feature (a small high-contrast detail the
//         body's MV dominates) → the previous-frame eye averaged onto the new one.
//     (2) the fallback blend_result = (1−t)·prev + t·cur is a static cross-fade =
//         a double exposure of moving content by construction.
//   Commit mode replaces averaging with COMMITMENT where the sources disagree:
//     · warp: per-pixel d_ab = max-channel abs diff (A_samp.rgb vs B_samp.rgb).
//       d_ab ≤ commit_thresh → keep the average (the MV is right here; averaging only
//       sharpens). d_ab > commit_thresh → the MV is wrong for THIS pixel → commit to
//       the temporally NEAREST sample (t<0.5 ? A_samp : B_samp; tie at 0.5 → B/cur,
//       forward-consistent, no flicker).
//     · fallback: blend_result becomes the nearest REAL sample (t<0.5 ? prev : cur;
//       tie → cur) instead of the cross-fade — identical for static content, kills the
//       old-frame double exposure for gated moving content.
//   commit_thresh == 0.0 (default OFF) takes the EXACT original averages below
//   (byte-identical — the whole commit path is gated on commit_thresh > 0.0, NOT on
//   d_ab, so any difference at thresh 0 does NOT trigger a commit). It composes with
//   soft mode: the soft branch reads the same (possibly committed) warp/blend results.
//
// ── STAGE-56: the stasis layer (the HUD fix) — push-selected, stasis_thresh > 0.0 ───────────
//   The operator's post-55 verdict: the pipeline is healthy (cons==arr, frz unpinned, lat 16-20ms);
//   the residual pain is contour hallucination, WORST on the HUD — static overlay pixels over a
//   moving world, damaged by EVERY motion-helping layer (the bilateral fetch lends them a moving
//   corner's MV; the rescue "rescues" their flat pixels with world vectors — the flat-content blind
//   spot at HUD edges; the matte classifies them dissident → object layer → dragged edges).
//   The answer is already in the SAD field: sad_zero is the per-tile in-place residual at MV=(0,0)
//   (built in the pillar's optical_flow_hier_match.comp, lines 88-95: a SUM over the 64 block pixels
//   of Σ_chan |A_chan − B_chan|, RGB, normalized [0,1] color units — range [0,192]). sad_zero ≈ 0
//   means the 8×8 block is IDENTICAL in both pair frames; its correct interpolation at ANY phase t
//   is THAT SAME content, untouched. So a stasis pixel BYPASSES all motion machinery and presents
//   the current frame's content directly.
//     · stz = texture(u_sad_field, uv).g  — sad_zero at this position (block-res, bilinear tap).
//     · stasis = (stasis_thresh > 0.0) && (stz <= stasis_thresh).
//     · APPLIED as the FINAL select, after the soft/hard selection produces `result`, immediately
//       before imageStore: `if (stasis) result = texture(u_cur_real, uv);`. This is the LAST word —
//       it DOMINATES warp/commit/matte/soft for stasis pixels (identical-content pixels are exact by
//       definition and immune to vector lending). Cost: ZERO extra — the SAD field is already bound
//       (Gate 1 reads it); one extra .g read, no new tap, no new binding, no new shared array.
//   stasis_thresh == 0.0 (default OFF, = --stasis not set) computes stz but `stasis` is always false
//   (the `> 0.0` short-circuits the comparison), so the override never fires → BYTE-IDENTICAL to
//   pre-STAGE-56. Honest tradeoffs (documented, not hidden):
//     (a) the SAD field is block-res (full-res/8); the bilinear .g tap smears the stasis boundary by
//         up to one block. Pixels NEAR a static block lean static — the SAFE direction (a stationary
//         pixel mis-helped is far worse than a moving pixel held one block; the held pixel is at most
//         one block stale at a boundary, which is sub-perceptual for HUD edges).
//     (b) a slowly-CHANGING HUD element (a ticking number/clock) has small NONZERO sad_zero and may
//         FLICKER between stasis/normal at the threshold tick-to-tick. The known cure is temporal
//         hysteresis (hold the stasis decision across a few ticks) — a LATER stage; not done here.
//
// ── Gate 1: Confidence (STAGE-20) ────────────────────────────────────────────
//   sad_best : residual at the winning MV (low = good match).
//   sad_zero : residual at MV=(0,0)       (low = static tile).
//   Passes iff:  (a) sad_best < residual_ceil
//                (b) sad_zero·(1 − improvement_frac) > sad_best   (no divide; cancels dither)
//
// ── Gate 2: Source agreement (STAGE-24) ──────────────────────────────────────
//   d = length(A_samp.rgb − B_samp.rgb); per-tile MEAN over the 8×8 workgroup (shared mem).
//   WARP iff both gates pass AND d_tile < agreement_threshold; else BLEND.
//
// Implementation note — why the barrier is unconditional (the divergence trap):
//   The MV is sampled via texture() (bilinear) so the per-tile gate decision is NOT
//   guaranteed uniform across the workgroup. The shared-memory barrier MUST therefore sit at
//   the top level of main(), OUTSIDE any conditional (uniform-control-flow — a Vulkan
//   requirement). An early return for out-of-bounds invocations would make the barrier
//   divergent → undefined behaviour (it happened to pass multiple-of-8 resolutions, which
//   spawn no edge invocations). So OOB invocations run the whole body (writing 0 to s_d so
//   the tile mean is unaffected) and only skip the final imageStore.
//
//   C_t(x) = (1−t)·A[x − t·mv] + t·B[x + (1−t)·mv]   (convention: MV points A→B; prev=A, cur=B)
#version 450
layout(local_size_x = 8, local_size_y = 8, local_size_z = 1) in;

layout(set = 0, binding = 0) uniform sampler2D u_prev_real;       // frame A (phase 0)
layout(set = 0, binding = 1) uniform sampler2D u_cur_real;        // frame B (phase 1)
layout(set = 0, binding = 2) uniform sampler2D u_motion_vectors;  // RG16F, finest level, pixel units
layout(set = 0, binding = 3) uniform sampler2D u_sad_field;       // RG16F: R=sad_best, G=sad_zero
layout(set = 0, binding = 4, rgba8) uniform writeonly image2D u_output;
layout(set = 0, binding = 5) uniform sampler2D u_motion_vectors_bwd; // STAGE-48: RG16F, cur→prev, pixel units
layout(set = 0, binding = 6) uniform sampler2D u_dissidence;      // STAGE-53: R8, |mv−model|/16px (mvw×mvh)
                                                                 //   The R8 store on the host is min(255, 16·r_px),
                                                                 //   so a sample reads v = 16·r_px/255 ∈ [0,1]:
                                                                 //   matte_thresh 0.25 ↔ r = 0.25·255/16 ≈ 4 px.
                                                                 //   This is the PREV-anchored (fwd) silhouette.
layout(set = 0, binding = 7) uniform sampler2D u_dissidence_bwd;  // STAGE-53b: R8, |mv_bwd−model_bwd|/16px (mvw×mvh)
                                                                 //   The CUR-anchored silhouette — the SAME quantization,
                                                                 //   fitted on the BACKWARD MV field. Advected BACKWARD in
                                                                 //   the matte decision, it covers the LEADING edge the
                                                                 //   prev-anchored mask arrives late at (the dual anchor).
                                                                 //   Bound always (valid view); read only when matte_on>0.5.
layout(set = 0, binding = 8) uniform sampler2D u_persistence;    // STAGE-57: R8, per-MV-block motion-state hysteresis
                                                                 //   counter / 255 ∈ [0,1] (the host stores persist∈[0,255]
                                                                 //   directly, so 16/255≈0.063 per sustained-static pair).
                                                                 //   A block with persistence ≥ inertia_thresh has a STATIC
                                                                 //   HISTORY → the three motion-restriction gates apply.
                                                                 //   Bound always (valid view); read only when inertia_thresh>0.5.
// ── STAGE-59: the laser mass counter — the PRESENTED matte occupancy (push-selected, matte_on>0.5) ──
//   The matte's phase-t silhouette is now the t-weighted INTERPOLATION of the two anchored occupancies
//   (mix(dis_fwd, dis_bwd, t) — see the matte decision block) rather than their union. The lerp can
//   THIN the silhouette at mid-t with imperfect masks (the union never did); the mass-conservation
//   feedback (P-side, --mass-k) is the counterweight. To close that loop the warp MEASURES the presented
//   mass: the number of pixels classified OBJECT (matte_object) this dispatch. A per-workgroup shared
//   reduction (s_matte_cnt) + ONE atomicAdd into this host-visible counter at local index 0 (NOT per
//   pixel) — the same one-atomicAdd-per-workgroup discipline the kickoff specifies. P resets it to 0
//   before each dispatch and reads it AFTER the existing fBridge fence wait (coherent, no stall). The
//   count is gated on matte_on>0.5 (a uniform push value) → when matte is off NOTHING is added (the
//   counter stays whatever P last reset it to, and --mass-k feedback is inert) → byte-identical output.
layout(set = 0, binding = 9) buffer MatteCounter { uint matte_count; } u_matte_counter;
// STAGE-77: the second-best CANDIDATE field (RGBA16F, mvw×mvh) — the matcher's RUNNER-UP per tile:
//   .xy = runner-up motion vector (pixel units), .z = runner-up pure SAD, .w = 0 (reserved). Bound ALWAYS
//   (a valid sampled view — wapC2A when use_ambig, else a placeholder = the MV view); the shader reads it
//   ONLY when ambig_on>0.5 (a uniform push value). Periodic textures (striped flags, concentric tunnels)
//   make the matcher resolve SAD TIES arbitrarily — the runner-up is the OTHER plausible vector, ~one
//   texture period away with a near-tied SAD; the ambiguity rule (the primary-MV site) arbitrates the tie
//   on background/texture-interior pixels against the gme model referee. Read only under ambig_on>0.5.
layout(set = 0, binding = 10) uniform sampler2D u_candidates;
// STAGE-90 (P2b): the iGPU image-derived CONTOUR FIELD (STAGE-G1, wapFIELDA, R32_UINT, full-res):
//   byte 0 = Sobel contour distance 0..255, byte 1 = occ-class (1 = edge-band). Read via imageLoad (an
//   INTEGER format, NOT sampleable) ONLY when bg_snap_on>0.5 — the background-snap disocclusion fix. Bound
//   ALWAYS (the warp-completeness discipline, like bindings 5/6/7/8/10: wapFIELDA when --bg-snap/--afill own
//   it, else a 1×1 r32ui placeholder), never read when off → byte-identical.
layout(set = 0, binding = 11, r32ui) uniform readonly uimage2D u_field;
// STAGE-94 (--vblend): the NEXT pair's forward MV field (RG16F, mvw×mvh, pixel units) — the
//   velocity-continuity TARGET. The present thread runs ~1 pair behind the freshest published
//   generation, so the next-fresher generation's MV grid is available "for free" in the F→P ring.
//   Sampled EXACTLY like u_motion_vectors (binding 2) / u_motion_vectors_bwd (binding 5): an rg16f
//   MV grid as a sampler2D. Bound ALWAYS (the warp-completeness discipline like bindings 5/10): the
//   real wapMVTA when --vblend owns it, else the forward MV view (wMV) as an unread placeholder. Read
//   ONLY when vblend_on>0.5 (a uniform push value) → never sampled when off → byte-identical.
layout(set = 0, binding = 12) uniform sampler2D u_mv_target;
// STAGE-97 (--ts-smooth): the PREVIOUS final output frame (RGBA8, full-res WW×WH) — the temporal-smoothing
//   history. The host copies wapOutA → wapPrevOutA after each tick's blit, so this holds LAST tick's presented
//   FG frame at the same uv (no motion-comp → it trails on moving content, hence the garbage-gate below confines
//   the blend to low-confidence/disocclusion pixels). Sampled EXACTLY like u_prev_real (binding 0). Bound ALWAYS
//   (the warp-completeness discipline like bindings 5/10/12): the real wapPrevOutA when --ts-smooth owns it, else
//   wapCurA as an unread placeholder. Read ONLY when ts_smooth>0 (a uniform push value) → never sampled when off
//   → byte-identical.
layout(set = 0, binding = 13) uniform sampler2D u_prev_out;
layout(push_constant) uniform PushConsts {
    float residual_ceil;
    float improvement_frac;
    float agreement_threshold;
    float t;          // temporal phase set by the presenter per output-clock tick
    float soft_gate;  // STAGE-46: 0 = binary gates (default); >0.5 = continuous blend
    float commit_thresh; // STAGE-47: 0 = average (default); >0 = commit-don't-hedge (color units)
    float commit_real;   // STAGE-47b: >0.5 = commit to the UNWARPED nearest real (no displaced
                         // fetch through the bad MV — kills the overdrive-like edge fringe at
                         // the cost of local source-cadence stepping); 0 = nearest WARPED sample.
    float occl_thresh;   // STAGE-48: 0 = bidir OFF (default, byte-identical); >0 = fwd↔bwd
                         // consistency threshold in PIXEL units (round-trip residual ≤ thresh =
                         // co-visible; above = occluded → one-sided sampling; default 1.5).
    float div_eps;       // STAGE-50: 0 = fill-div OFF (default, byte-identical); >0 = divergence
                         // band for the bidir neither-class sliver (pixels/MV-grid-texel). div >
                         // +div_eps → revealed → sample cur; div < −div_eps → occluded → sample
                         // prev; |div| ≤ div_eps → fall through to 47b/c. Requires occl_thresh>0.
    float rescue_on;     // STAGE-49: 0 = candidate-rescue OFF (default, byte-identical); >0.5 = a pixel
                         // whose primary MV fails the d_ab commit trigger tries the 8 NEIGHBOR block MVs
                         // (3×3 fwd field) first; if the best candidate's two warped samples agree
                         // ≤ commit_thresh it is RESCUED (warp = that candidate's average, commit skipped).
                         // Requires commit_thresh>0 (the commit trigger). 4+16 extra taps WORST case,
                         // only in the already-failing branch.
    float mv_guided;     // STAGE-49c: 0 = LINEAR MV upsampling (default, byte-identical); >0.5 = bilateral
                         // (color-membership) PRIMARY MV fetch — texelFetch the 4 surrounding MV-grid
                         // corners, sample cur_real at each corner's block centre, pick the corner whose
                         // centre color is closest (max-channel) to this pixel's color; near-tie / none-
                         // similar → the standard LINEAR texture() result. The selected mv feeds
                         // EVERYTHING downstream exactly as the bilinear mv did. ENCODING: the host packs
                         // the membership band as mv_guided = 1.0 + sim_thresh (sim∈[0.02,0.5] → 1.02..1.5,
                         // so >0.5 gates ON and sim = mv_guided−1.0 is the --mv-sim value). Set --mv-guided.
    float gme_on;        // STAGE-52: 0 = frame-holon OFF (default, byte-identical); >0.5 = the global
                         // affine motion model is armed. When on it adds ONE extra rescue candidate (the
                         // model MV, scored by the same windowed SAD) inside the rescue loop, and directs
